properties.Title: Flood Warning Being Issued For The Red River At St. Adolphe
properties.Summary:
Description: This is a Manitoba Emergency Alert. Manitoba Infrastructure's Hydrologic Forecast Centre has issued a Flood Warning on the Red River at St. Adolphe due to operation of the Red River Floodway. If you are in the affected area, be watchful of local waterways as flooding is likely to occur. Do not attempt to cross fast flowing waters or waters of unknown depth. Avoid flooded areas. Follow all directions given by local authorities. Listen for updates and take all necessary precautions to stay safe. Up-to-date information is available at www.gov.mb.ca/flooding and www.manitoba511.ca or stay tuned to local media.
Expires: 2019-10-15T15:15:00-05:00

Area: The Red River at St. Adolphe
properties.Author: Manitoba Emergency Measures Organization

properties.Title: Special Weather Statement In Effect
properties.Summary:
Description: Rain and wind on Thursday. An intense low pressure system will track towards the region on Thursday. Rain and wind will begin Thursday afternoon and persist into the evening. Total rainfall amounts of 20 to 40 mm are expected. Additionally, easterly wind gusts of 70 km/h or higher are likely and may reach warning criteria of 90 km/h. Higher than normal water levels and rough surf is also possible near high tide Thursday evening. ### Please continue to monitor alerts and forecasts issued by Environment Canada. To report severe weather, send an email to NSstorm@canada.ca or tweet reports using #NSStorm.

properties.Title: Blizzard Warning In Effect
properties.Summary:
Description: Blizzard conditions with poor visibility in snow and blowing snow are expected or occurring. An area of high pressure building over the Mackenzie River Basin and an intense low pressure system approaching the Gulf of Alaska will produce blizzard conditions along the Dempster Highway near the Richardson mountains. Easterly winds of 80 km/h will develop Tuesday morning and persist until Wednesday evening. The strong winds, light falling snow and existing snow pack will combine to reduce visibilities for the period. ### Travel is expected to be hazardous due to reduced visibility. Please continue to monitor alerts and forecasts issued by Environment Canada. To report severe weather in British Columbia or Yukon, send an email to BCstorm@canada.ca or YTstorm@canada.ca or tweet reports using #BCStorm or #YTStorm.
Expires: 2019-10-16T07:25:26-00:00
Originated from CAP Alert: Environment Canada, 2019-10-15T15:26:26-00:00, urn:oid:2.49.0.1.124.2896480376.2019
Area: Dempster
properties.Author: Environment Canada

properties.Title: Snowfall Warning In Effect
properties.Summary:
Description: A long period of snowfall with total amounts of 10 to 20 cm is expected. A strong Pacific frontal system slowly tracking across northern British Columbia will give 10 to 20 cm of snow to the Cassiar Mountains. Snow will taper off Tuesday evening with flurries persisting until Wednesday morning. ### Please continue to monitor alerts and forecasts issued by Environment Canada. To report severe weather in British Columbia or Yukon, send an email to BCstorm@canada.ca or YTstorm@canada.ca or tweet reports using #BCStorm or #YTStorm.
